the final 20 miles.

31:46.372 --> 31:47.938
- After tomorrow I don't know

31:47.940 --> 31:50.240
if they'll get anymore freight
in here or not.

31:50.242 --> 31:51.642
(truck rattles)

31:53.012 --> 31:54.411
I need to get unloaded

31:54.413 --> 31:56.013
and get the (bleep)
out of here.

32:00.920 --> 32:02.386
(wind gusts)

32:02.388 --> 32:04.454
narrator: As the sun sets...

32:06.525 --> 32:08.525
Darrell: I pulled into brochet
here.

32:08.527 --> 32:10.627
Narrator: ...A weary darrell
completes

32:10.629 --> 32:13.363
the final piece of his epic
journey.

32:13.365 --> 32:14.798
(airbrakes hiss)

32:16.201 --> 32:17.801
darrell: Let's get 'er done.

32:19.138 --> 32:21.038
At least it's only half full.

32:21.040 --> 32:23.173
I survived the roads,

32:23.175 --> 32:25.542
communities got
what they needed.

32:27.913 --> 32:29.413
Can we get out of here before
the weather turns warm?

32:29.415 --> 32:31.848
I might end up living
in brochet if I don't.

32:33.252 --> 32:35.185
Narrator: As the season enters
into the home stretch,

32:35.187 --> 32:37.721
darrell scores big
for his company

32:37.723 --> 32:41.224
and for the communities
when they needed it most.

32:42.594 --> 32:44.328
- Against all odds
we pulled it off.

32:45.664 --> 32:47.164
Narrator: The small company's
bagged

32:47.166 --> 32:49.499
four total hauls in a day,

32:49.501 --> 32:52.302
but 500 miles to the southeast,

32:52.304 --> 32:54.438
late into the night...

32:55.774 --> 32:57.574
Todd: Trying to get 'er going
here good, boys.

32:57.576 --> 32:59.576
I had a nice hot fire tonight.

32:59.578 --> 33:01.578
They closed the road right
in front of me,

33:01.580 --> 33:02.980
parked me for the day.

33:02.982 --> 33:05.315
Narrator: Todd dewey's
celebrating his birthday

33:05.317 --> 33:07.985
stuck at the turn off
to big trout lake.

33:07.987 --> 33:09.553
Todd: So why not take advantage
of it.

33:09.555 --> 33:11.989
You know, enjoy what the good
lord gave us out here.

33:11.991 --> 33:13.523
It's absolutely beautiful.

33:13.525 --> 33:15.625
Narrator: Earlier...

33:15.627 --> 33:17.728
Todd: What in the hell?

33:19.264 --> 33:20.897
- The road's closed, huh?
Man: Yeah.

33:20.899 --> 33:23.600
Narrator: ...Warm weather
proved too much for the road

33:23.602 --> 33:26.470
and authorities were forced
to shut it down.

33:26.472 --> 33:28.572
Todd: All right, buddy.

33:28.574 --> 33:32.042
Narrator: Since then todd's
been sidelined for hours

33:32.044 --> 33:34.845
waiting until temperatures
hopefully cool down

33:34.847 --> 33:37.047
enough for travel.

33:37.049 --> 33:39.449
Todd: You know,
there's only one thing

33:39.451 --> 33:41.151
that's really been on my mind
that I'd really like to do

33:41.153 --> 33:42.819
and you know we're not supposed
to use the sat phone.

33:44.189 --> 33:46.089
Only for emergency uses,

33:46.091 --> 33:47.758
but you know what,
it's my birthday,

33:47.760 --> 33:49.526
I'm in the middle of nowhere.

33:49.528 --> 33:53.663
I'm gonna call my wife even
if it's just for 20 seconds.

33:53.665 --> 33:55.198
I know she's thinking
about it right now

33:55.200 --> 33:56.733
wondering where I'm at

33:56.735 --> 33:58.869
and what I'm doing
and if I'm okay.

33:58.871 --> 34:03.306
♪ ♪

34:03.308 --> 34:05.876
hi. (laughs)

34:05.878 --> 34:08.278
I knew you'd say
happy birthday.

34:08.280 --> 34:10.213
Listen, honey,
I've only got a minute.

34:11.583 --> 34:14.017
I love you guys too.
I miss you guys like crazy.

34:15.654 --> 34:18.455
I know can you believe
I'm only 25 years old?

34:18.457 --> 34:19.890
(laughs)

34:19.892 --> 34:21.658
you wish? Yeah, so do I.

34:23.028 --> 34:25.662
Being away from my family's
already hard enough,

34:25.664 --> 34:27.130
when it's your birthday

34:27.132 --> 34:29.132
and you're in the middle
of pretty much nowhere,

34:29.134 --> 34:31.368
by yourself,

34:31.370 --> 34:33.203
it-it can get to ya.

34:33.205 --> 34:35.439
It gives you that sense
of loneliness.

34:36.809 --> 34:38.742
I love you too, honey.

34:40.179 --> 34:43.146
Okay, tell the kids daddy
loves them and I miss them.

34:44.550 --> 34:45.949
All right, bye.

34:47.319 --> 34:49.219
That right there make a guy
get tears in his eyes

34:49.221 --> 34:50.720
missing his family.

34:53.225 --> 34:54.825
Yeah, that's all she wrote.

34:59.665 --> 35:02.232
Narrator: With the community
desperate for supplies...

35:02.234 --> 35:04.601
Todd: Finally.

35:04.603 --> 35:06.336
Narrator: ...And temperatures
as low as they'll get for
the night...

35:06.338 --> 35:07.771
Todd: Here we go.

35:07.773 --> 35:10.340
Narrator: ...Locals are willing
to let todd roll.

35:11.710 --> 35:13.143
Todd: Oh she's gonna be
a long night, boys,

35:13.145 --> 35:14.511
I'm telling ya.

35:14.513 --> 35:15.946
Yeah, after sitting around
for 12 hours

35:15.948 --> 35:17.347
waiting for the road to open

35:17.349 --> 35:18.715
and now we gotta truck for
another 12 hours straight

35:18.717 --> 35:20.150
to get through this road.

35:22.521 --> 35:23.920
It's gonna be a hard road
to conquer, I'm telling ya.

35:23.922 --> 35:24.354
(engine hums)

35:26.959 --> 35:28.425
(truck rattles)
hang on.

35:29.761 --> 35:31.161
Narrator: The road may be open,

35:31.163 --> 35:33.563
(todd sighs)

35:33.565 --> 35:35.599
narrator: ...But the muskeg's
barely frozen if at all.

35:36.969 --> 35:39.336
Todd: Hang on.

35:39.338 --> 35:41.571
Narrator: And it's pulverizing
todd and his 20-ton load.

35:41.573 --> 35:43.540
(truck groans, rattles)

35:45.477 --> 35:46.910
(engine hums)

35:48.247 --> 35:50.280
- if I get stuck on this trip
to big trout,

35:50.282 --> 35:51.948
I'm screwed.

35:51.950 --> 35:53.383
(creaking)

35:53.385 --> 35:55.719
there ain't gonna be nobody
here to pull us out.

35:55.721 --> 35:57.120
(engine hums)

35:58.490 --> 36:01.124
(truck rattles)

36:02.528 --> 36:03.994
that's what makes a guy
so nervous.

36:03.996 --> 36:05.295
You're just thinking,

36:05.297 --> 36:06.663
"please don't get stuck,
please don't get stuck."

36:06.665 --> 36:08.098
(truck rattles)

36:12.104 --> 36:13.937
what did I get myself into?

36:18.143 --> 36:20.510
Narrator: As the clock
strikes 4:00 a.M. ...

36:23.148 --> 36:25.815
- We got a lot of miles
to cover all night tonight.

36:25.817 --> 36:28.018
Narrator:...Todd's night takes
an even darker turn.

36:29.388 --> 36:31.121
Todd: Oh, my effing god.

36:33.625 --> 36:36.059
So I just came screaming
around a corner

36:36.061 --> 36:38.528
and now I'm right into
an ice crossing so...

36:39.932 --> 36:42.098
Trying to see what's going on.

36:44.269 --> 36:46.002
Narrator: Todd's the only
trucker

36:46.004 --> 36:48.305
to pass down the road
to big trout.

36:49.641 --> 36:52.876
Now he'll be the only one
to test the ice crossing.

36:52.878 --> 36:54.311
(ice cracking)

36:56.381 --> 36:59.482
- a little sketchy on the ice
crossing coming in here.

36:59.484 --> 37:03.320
♪ ♪

37:03.322 --> 37:06.423
they haven't had any big rigs
in here to big trout yet.

37:06.425 --> 37:07.857
(ice cracking)

37:10.128 --> 37:12.262
todd: That (bleep) makes a guy
nervous.

37:12.264 --> 37:14.264
(bleep).

37:15.634 --> 37:17.300
When you're the first truck
up the road

37:17.302 --> 37:21.137
or the first truck going across
the ice, you know,

37:21.139 --> 37:23.873
you know, there's supposed
to be a certain thickness.

37:23.875 --> 37:26.409
All actuality you don't know
how thick the ice is

37:26.411 --> 37:28.211
and you don't know
if it's ready to go.

37:28.213 --> 37:29.646
(ice cracking)

37:31.016 --> 37:32.449
even though you can try
to convince yourself

37:32.451 --> 37:34.651
I've been across these ice
crossings a hundred times

37:34.653 --> 37:36.620
that doesn't mean jack-crap.

37:36.622 --> 37:38.154
That just means that
you've been lucky

37:38.156 --> 37:40.590
all those other times

37:40.592 --> 37:42.058
and maybe this one time your
luck has finally run out.

37:43.562 --> 37:44.995
These are the nights
it just doesn't seem

37:44.997 --> 37:46.730
like my job's really worth it.

37:46.732 --> 37:52.936
♪ ♪

37:52.938 --> 37:54.371
(door shuts)

37:54.373 --> 37:57.741
well, there's only one thing
to do.

38:00.078 --> 38:02.479
It's to get (bleep) going.

38:02.481 --> 38:03.913
(chains clink)

38:05.517 --> 38:06.950
(engine hums)

38:09.321 --> 38:10.820
it's always nerve wracking
at night to go across the ice.

38:10.822 --> 38:12.255
(ice cracking)

38:13.659 --> 38:15.025
- no stoppin' now.

38:15.027 --> 38:16.459
(ice cracking)

38:21.233 --> 38:22.632
narrator: In the dead of night

38:24.002 --> 38:25.702
in northern ontario...

38:27.072 --> 38:29.706
- Well, there's only one thing
to do

38:31.076 --> 38:33.376
is to get (bleep) going.

38:33.378 --> 38:37.180
Narrator:...Todd dewey's
rolling the dice.

38:37.182 --> 38:38.648
(engine hums)

38:40.285 --> 38:41.718
(ice cracking)

38:43.855 --> 38:45.522
- no stoppin' now.

38:46.892 --> 38:50.093
Narrator: The road to big trout
just opened hours ago...

38:50.095 --> 38:51.528
- Always nerve wracking
at night

38:51.530 --> 38:52.896
to go across the ice.

38:52.898 --> 38:54.931
Narrator: ...And todd's
the first big rig

38:54.933 --> 38:57.834
to test the crossing
all season.

38:57.836 --> 38:59.536
Todd: You never get used to
that loud cracking

38:59.538 --> 39:02.072
and popping on the ice at night
that's for sure.

39:03.408 --> 39:04.874
It's a big-(bleep) lake too.

39:06.144 --> 39:07.544
You don't know how long it is.

39:07.546 --> 39:09.412
See, you don't know
if you got an hour,

39:09.414 --> 39:11.381
two hours, 20 minutes,
five minutes,

39:11.383 --> 39:12.782
you just don't know.

39:12.784 --> 39:15.185
I mean, you just go on it,
keep your fingers crossed.

39:15.187 --> 39:16.720
(chains clink)

39:18.123 --> 39:19.923
(engine hums)

39:23.028 --> 39:25.095
you can tell it hasn't been
plowed properly.

39:25.097 --> 39:26.730
The ice is rough.

39:26.732 --> 39:28.131
It shouldn't be rough.

39:28.133 --> 39:31.167
It should be nice smooth
clean ice.

39:31.169 --> 39:32.702
(ice cracking)

39:34.973 --> 39:37.974
I'm not even sure if I passed
the halfway point.

39:37.976 --> 39:47.350
♪ ♪

39:47.352 --> 39:48.818
todd: Imagine if you went
through at night?

39:50.455 --> 39:52.856
At least during the day light
you come up out of the water

39:52.858 --> 39:54.524
if you do and you get,

39:54.526 --> 39:56.426
you can actually see
what you're doing

39:56.428 --> 39:58.928
and try to grab a hold
of something or anything.

39:58.930 --> 40:00.630
In the dk...

40:02.000 --> 40:04.000
...You ain't gonna find nothing
to (bleep) grab a hold of.

40:05.670 --> 40:07.103
As soon as this truck goes
underwater

40:07.105 --> 40:08.505
you ain't gonna see nothing.

40:08.507 --> 40:10.807
It'll be pitch black.

40:10.809 --> 40:15.211
♪ ♪

40:15.213 --> 40:17.914
pretty darn spooky this time of
the morning crossing the ice.

40:19.317 --> 40:21.117
Look at that crack right there.

40:21.119 --> 40:22.919
Look at that (bleep).

40:24.656 --> 40:26.723
I hate crossing
the ice at night.

40:28.493 --> 40:29.926
(ice cracking)

40:31.263 --> 40:32.829
the road in front of me,
I'm seeing some trees now

40:32.831 --> 40:34.264
so that's a good sign.

40:35.634 --> 40:38.968
That means I'm getting close
to getting off the ice.

40:38.970 --> 40:42.205
So close but yet so far away.

40:43.575 --> 40:45.942
Come on, girl. Come on!

40:47.479 --> 40:48.912
(ice cracking)

40:50.282 --> 40:51.714
(engine roars)

40:53.385 --> 40:55.919
all right, off the ice, baby.

40:55.921 --> 40:57.821
Yes!

40:57.823 --> 41:00.390
Narrator: Todd makes it off
the ice...

41:01.760 --> 41:03.159
- I don't know how many
we got to go,

41:03.161 --> 41:04.561
but I know we got a lot
of miles to cover

41:04.563 --> 41:06.095
all night tonight.

41:06.097 --> 41:08.698
Narrator:...But he's still got
over 200 miles

41:08.700 --> 41:11.434
of brutal winter road
ahead of him.

41:11.436 --> 41:14.003
- It's gonna be one hell
of a journey

41:14.005 --> 41:15.705
I'm telling you right now.

41:15.707 --> 41:17.140
(engine hums)

41:18.543 --> 41:19.943
(truck rattles)

41:22.247 --> 41:24.013
oh, (bleep)!
Come on, buddy.

41:25.417 --> 41:27.650
Nasty-(bleep) frickin' road,
man.

41:30.021 --> 41:31.788
They're just getting more
harder and more treacherous

41:31.790 --> 41:33.189
trying to get through it.

41:33.191 --> 41:34.791
It's just getting ridiculous.

41:34.793 --> 41:35.959
All I'm gonna do is just keep
on trucking.

41:35.961 --> 41:38.061
(truck rattles)

41:38.063 --> 41:39.762
(thud)

41:39.764 --> 41:41.764
(truck rattles)

41:43.101 --> 41:44.934
what the hell?

41:44.936 --> 41:46.402
(rattling)

41:49.307 --> 41:51.441
I gotta look at something here.

41:56.748 --> 41:58.214
(airbrakes hiss)

42:02.521 --> 42:03.987
(wind gusts)

42:10.629 --> 42:12.028
this truck is done.

42:12.030 --> 42:13.496
It's not moving on its own
from right here

42:13.498 --> 42:15.131
for any way shape or form.

42:15.133 --> 42:16.766
That's the spring
that holds the axel

42:16.768 --> 42:18.601
on the front of the truck.

42:18.603 --> 42:21.638
Narrator: With the spring
to the front axle broken

42:21.640 --> 42:24.941
the truck is virtually
un-drivable.

42:24.943 --> 42:26.309
(door shuts)

42:26.311 --> 42:28.011
todd: That's it,
the truck is stuck.

42:28.013 --> 42:30.113
There ain't no going back.

42:30.115 --> 42:32.682
I cannot (bleep) believe it,
man.

42:32.684 --> 42:35.919
Narrator: So hundreds of miles
from the nearest town,

42:35.921 --> 42:39.022
todd and his rig
are down for the count.

42:40.625 --> 42:42.659
Todd: We're just so (bleep).

42:42.661 --> 42:44.527
(wind gusts)

42:46.331 --> 42:47.764
narrator: Next time...

42:47.766 --> 42:50.366
Alex: This road is rotting
away underneath us.

42:50.368 --> 42:52.535
Narrator:...On "ice road
truckers"...

42:52.537 --> 42:53.937
(thud)
alex: Hang on.

42:53.939 --> 42:55.405
(truck rattles)

42:56.741 --> 42:59.375
narrator:...The melt descends
on the winter roads.

42:59.377 --> 43:01.978
- I'm gonna try hard to just
not to go in the ditch.

43:01.980 --> 43:04.280
Narrator: And for the drivers
it spells trouble.

43:05.850 --> 43:06.916
(thud)
- ah!
